  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent and report money laundering. These typically include:\n\n1. Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Conducting background checks\n- Monitoring suspicious transactions\n\n2. Reporting requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Alerting authorities to potential money laundering activities\n\n3. Anti-Money Laundering (AML) compliance programs\n- Developing internal policies and procedures\n- Training employees\n- Implementing transaction monitoring systems\n\n4. Record-keeping regulations\n- Maintaining detailed transaction records\n- Keeping customer identification documents\n- Preserving financial transaction histories\n\n5. Risk assessment\n- Identifying high-risk customers and transactions\n- Implementing enhanced due diligence for complex cases\n\n6. International cooperation\n- Sharing information across jurisdictions\n- Complying with global anti-money laundering standards\n\n7. Potential penalties\n- Significant financial fines\n- Potential criminal liability\n- Loss of banking licenses\n\nThese obligations are typically enforced through laws like the Bank Secrecy Act and international frameworks such as FATF recommendations.",
